1.DNS Server >> website name to IP of the server.
2.GET Request >> client can request a page in return to the server [/index.html]
3.If the page uses resources like JS, image, CSS they will be requested in separate GET Request.
4.HTTPS >> HTTP with TLS 1.3 encryption. ==> secure.

***HTTP Methods***
1.GET >> request data from the server
2.POST >> send data to server 
There are other methods that aren't used frequently

***Responses***

    Informational responses (100–199)
    Successful responses (200–299)
    Redirects (300–399)
    Client errors (400–499)
    Server errors (500–599)

Ref:https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status


***Cookies***
Small bits of data in the browser.
Cookies ==> sessions management and advertising
Why cookies? ==> As HTTP is stateless, cookies are used to keep track of the activity.
Cookies can have ==> name, value, an expiry date and path 
Server allocates the cookie to the client. >> sometimes JS in the browser
Ref:https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Cookies


***Curl***
-X GET or POST
-b cookie
--data "Whatever to be sent"

